# Commenting Standards

## Docstrings

Every module, class, function, method, and fixture must have a docstring — including inner closures, decorators, and nested callbacks. One-liners are fine when the signature is self-explanatory.

```python
# BAD — missing docstring on inner function
def cooldown(seconds: float) -> Callable:
    def decorator(fn):
        @functools.wraps(fn)
        async def wrapper(event):
            ...
        return wrapper
    return decorator

# GOOD — every layer documented
def cooldown(seconds: float) -> Callable:
    """Enforce a per-user cooldown on a command handler."""
    def decorator(fn):
        """Wrap fn with cooldown enforcement, preserving its signature."""
        @functools.wraps(fn)
        async def wrapper(event):
            """Check the cooldown window and delegate to the original handler."""
            ...
        return wrapper
    return decorator
```

## Inline Comments

Inline comments explain **why** or **what trade-off** — never narrate what the code already says. If the code is clear on its own, no comment is needed.

```python
# BAD — restates the code
# Loop through entries
for entry in entries:
    ...

# BAD — obvious from context
# Check if case_id is None
if case_id is None:

# GOOD — explains a non-obvious reason
# Flush to assign entry.id so we can link child documents below
await session.flush()

# GOOD — explains a trade-off or constraint
# Delete-then-insert: LlamaIndex has no atomic replace, so purge stale nodes first
index.delete_ref_doc(doc_id, delete_from_docstore=True)
```

## Section Separators

Never use `# -------` or `# =======` banner comments to label code sections. The code structure and docstrings provide organization. Remove them when you encounter them.

```python
# BAD
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Exceptions
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

class MyError(Exception): ...

# GOOD — the class docstring provides all needed context
class MyError(Exception):
    """Raised when a command requires a higher permission level."""
```

## Loguru

Use `{}` placeholder syntax, not f-strings, for all loguru calls.

```python
# BAD
logger.error(f"Sync failed for case {case_id}: {exc}")

# GOOD — lazy evaluation, structured-logging friendly
logger.error("Sync failed for case {}: {}", case_id, exc)
```
